Handling missing values:¶










In [7]:



     


df_all = df.append(df_test)  #train & test by appending them

#handling missing values
df_all[df_all=='?'] = np.nan  #make the ones that written "?" NaN (missing value)
df_all[['blood pressure','heart rate','cholestoral ']] = df_all[['blood pressure','heart rate','cholestoral ']].fillna(df_all[['blood pressure','heart rate','cholestoral ']].mean()) #fill NaN of numerical features with mean
df_all = df_all.fillna(0) #fill the rests (boolean features) with 0

#Scaling
MMS = MinMaxScaler() #first step (object)                    #the results of Scalers are Numpy array
df_all.iloc[:,:-1] = MMS.fit_transform(df_all.iloc[:,:-1]) #It is not necessary to use iloc, because the last column(Y) is boolean; however we can separate it!

#separating the data of "train" and "test" after all required pre-processing steps on df_all
df, df_test = df_all[:len(df)], df_all[len(df):]
df_test = df_test.drop('label', axis=1)

Note: In an imbalanced classification problem with two classes, recall is calculated as the number of true positives divided by the total number of true positives and false negatives.¶
    

  • Recall = TruePositives / (TruePositives + FalseNegatives)
    • 












In [11]:



     


tree = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=2, criterion='gini')
pred = cross_val_predict(tree, X_q, Y, cv=5)
r0 = recall_score(Y, pred, pos_label=0)
r1 = recall_score(Y, pred, pos_label=1)
print(r0, r1)

#Because it is an inbalanced classification, Label (0 is way less than 1 → the model cannot learn better and the prediction would not be good!)

In [12]:



     


tree = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=2, criterion='gini')
pred = cross_val_predict(tree, X_q, Y, cv=5)
r0 = recall_score(Y, pred, pos_label=0) #comparing our target(Y) with the prediction
r1 = recall_score(Y, pred, pos_label=1)
print(0.35*r0+0.65*r1)  #weighted mean recall



     


















    
    






0.5759140271493213




















Costum scoring by def function¶










In [13]:



     


#1st step

def weighted_mean_recall(y, yhat): #Y is target, Yhat is pred
    r0 = recall_score(y, yhat, pos_label=0)
    r1 = recall_score(y, yhat, pos_label=1)
    return 0.35*r0 + 0.65*r1



     















In [14]:



     


#2nd step

from sklearn.metrics import make_scorer
my_scorer = make_scorer(weighted_mean_recall, greater_is_better=True) # "greater is better" ► the more the score, the better 



     















Parameter tuning by GridSearchCV¶










In [15]:



     


tree = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42)
par = {'criterion':['gini','entropy'],
       'max_depth':[2,3,4,5,6],
       'min_samples_split':[2,3,4,5],
       'class_weight':['balanced',{0:0.1,1:0.9},{0:0.2,1:0.8}]} #This is the most parameter for this model, cuz our target is imbalanced.
GS = GridSearchCV(tree, param_grid=par, cv=5, scoring=my_scorer)
GS.fit(X_q, Y)



     


















    
    
Out[15]:








GridSearchCV(cv=5, estimator=DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42),
             param_grid={'class_weight': ['balanced', {0: 0.1, 1: 0.9},

                         'criterion': ['gini', 'entropy'],
                         'max_depth': [2, 3, 4, 5, 6],
                         'min_samples_split': [2, 3, 4, 5]},
             scoring=make_scorer(weighted_mean_recall))
